{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fbaf46b6-2d14-495e-bb66-a569aa72a24c","content":"I can help guide you through analyzing your .NET crash dump. Here are the main approaches:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n- `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` — inspect specific threads\n\n**Using WinDbg** (Windows, richer for native interop):\n- Load dump → `.loadby sos clr` or `.loadby sos coreclr`\n- `!pe` — print exception\n- `!clrstack` — managed stack\n- `!analyze -v` — automated crash analysis\n\n**Using LLDB + SOS** (Linux/macOS):\n```bash\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\npe\n```\n\n**Quick triage steps:**\n1. Run `pe` first to check if an unhandled exception caused the crash\n2. Run `threads` to find the faulting thread\n3. Run `clrstack` on that thread to see the managed call stack\n\nWould you like help running any of these tools on your dump file, or do you have questions about interpreting specific output?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98a4e8ae-7887-4ff8-bbe1-f240c9964407","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET app. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description specifically says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here since the user wants to analyze a dump, not collect one.\n\nI should provide guidance on analyzing .NET crash dumps without invoking that skill.","outputTokens":486,"requestId":"5030:11A527:27A00C:31D6C5:69F555